  "Question": "<p>Let <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_563\"><math alttext=\"a\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mi>a</mi></semantics></math></span>,<span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_564\"><math alttext=\"b\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mi>b</mi></semantics></math></span> be relatively prime integers which are both greater than or equal to <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_565\"><math alttext=\"2\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mn>2</mn></semantics></math></span> . Show that <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_566\"><math alttext=\"(a/b)^{2}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><msup><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>b</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></msup></semantics></math></span> cannot be an integer.</p> <p>I have tried to use contradiction to prove this result, but I am not sure that my idea is correct or not. Below is my idea (not a complete proof).</p> <p>Suppose <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_567\"><math alttext=\"(a/b)^{2}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><msup><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>b</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></msup></semantics></math></span> be an integer. We have <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_568\"><math alttext=\"a/b\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>b</mi></mrow></semantics></math></span> is an integer. Then, we have <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_569\"><math alttext=\"a=bk\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mrow><mi>b</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mi>k</mi></mrow></mrow></semantics></math></span> where <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_570\"><math alttext=\"k\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mi>k</mi></semantics></math></span> is an integer since <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_571\"><math alttext=\"b\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mi>b</mi></semantics></math></span> divides <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_572\"><math alttext=\"a\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mi>a</mi></semantics></math></span>. Since <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_573\"><math alttext=\"a,b\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>b</mi></mrow></semantics></math></span> are relatively prime, therefore <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_574\"><math alttext=\"b\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mi>b</mi></semantics></math></span> must be <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_575\"><math alttext=\"1\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mn>1</mn></semantics></math></span>. Hence, contradiction arises. I am not sure that my idea is correct or not, could anyone help me to check it? If my idea is wrong, could you give me a idea to do this question?</p>",
  "Title": "How to show that <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_562\"><math alttext=\"(a/b)^{2}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><msup><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>b</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></msup></semantics></math></span> in this situation cannot be an integer",
